The command docker exec -it mysql-container mysq0l -uroot -proot123 is used to open an interactive terminal session
inside a running container to execute MySQL commands directly. By using the docker exec instruction, you are telling the Docker 
engine to start a new process within the environment of the container named mysql-container.
The -it flag is a combination of --interactive (keeping STDIN open) and --tty (allocating a pseudo-terminal),
which together allow you to type SQL queries and receive real-time feedback as if you were logged directly into a physical server.
Once inside the container, the command invokes the mysql client utility. The -u flag specifies the username—in this case, root—while
the -p flag is followed immediately by the password root123 without any spaces. While this method is convenient for quick access, it
is worth noting that including the password directly in the command string can leave it visible in your shell's command history, which
may pose a security risk in shared environments.
To ensure this command works, the mysql-container must currently be in a "running" state; if the container has been stopped or removed
(using the docker stop or docker rm commands you mentioned earlier), the execution will fail. This specific command logs you into the 
global MySQL prompt, allowing you to perform administrative tasks like creating databases, managing users, or querying any schema currently
hosted within that specific container instance.
